nodes.label: Logic gates
nodes.title: Logic gates
nodes.description: Logic gates: Electronic circuits that perform basic logical operations on one or more binary inputs to produce a single binary output, including AND, OR, NOT, NAND, NOR, and XOR gates.

nodes.label: CPU performance factors
nodes.title: CPU performance factors
nodes.description: CPU performance factors: CPU performance factors: Various aspects affecting the performance of a CPU, including clock speed, instruction count, and CPI (cycles per instruction).

nodes.label: Instruction count
nodes.title: Instruction count
nodes.description: Instruction count: Instruction count: The total number of instructions executed by a program, influencing the overall execution time.

nodes.label: CPI and cycle time
nodes.title: CPI and cycle time
nodes.description: CPI and cycle time: CPI and cycle time: CPI (cycles per instruction) represents the average number of clock cycles per instruction, while cycle time is the duration of one clock cycle.

nodes.label: MIPS
nodes.title: MIPS
nodes.description: MIPS: MIPS: Millions of Instructions Per Second, a metric used to measure the performance of a CPU by calculating how many millions of instructions it can execute in one second.

nodes.label: Hazards
nodes.title: Hazards
nodes.description: Hazards: Hazards: Situations that can affect the smooth execution of instructions, including structure hazards, data hazards, and control hazards.

nodes.label: Structure hazards
nodes.title: Structure hazards
nodes.description: Structure hazards: Structure hazards: Arise when the hardware cannot execute the next instruction in the pipeline during the current clock cycle due to structural limitations.

nodes.label: Data hazards
nodes.title: Data hazards
nodes.description: Data hazards: Data hazards: Occur when an instruction depends on the result of a previous instruction that has not yet been computed.

nodes.label: Control hazards
nodes.title: Control hazards
nodes.description: Control hazards: Control hazards: Arise when the pipeline makes a decision on the next instruction before the current instruction's effect on the program state is known.

nodes.label: Memory Hierarchy
nodes.title: Memory Hierarchy
nodes.description: Memory Hierarchy: Memory Hierarchy: The arrangement of different types of memory in a computer system, organized in a hierarchy based on access speed, capacity, and cost.

nodes.label: Memory wall
nodes.title: Memory wall
nodes.description: Memory wall: Memory wall: The growing performance gap between processor speeds and memory access times, leading to slower performance due to memory latency.

nodes.label: Principle of locality
nodes.title: Principle of locality
nodes.description: Principle of locality: Principle of locality: The observation that most programs access a small portion of their address space frequently, leading to the exploitation of temporal and spatial locality for improving memory access performance.

nodes.label: Temporal locality
nodes.title: Temporal locality
nodes.description: Temporal locality: Temporal locality: The tendency of a program to access the same memory locations repeatedly over a short period of time.

nodes.label: Spatial locality
nodes.title: Spatial locality
nodes.description: Spatial locality: Spatial locality: The tendency of a program to access memory locations that are close to each other in address space.

nodes.label: DRAM organization
nodes.title: DRAM organization
nodes.description: DRAM organization: DRAM organization: Dynamic Random Access Memory organization, referring to the structure and operation of DRAM modules, including the arrangement of rows and columns for storing data.

nodes.label: Multiprocessors
nodes.title: Multiprocessors
nodes.description: Multiprocessors: Multiprocessors: Computer systems with multiple processing units (CPUs) that work together to execute tasks concurrently, providing improved performance and scalability.

nodes.label: Flynn taxonomy
nodes.title: Flynn taxonomy
nodes.description: Flynn taxonomy: Flynn taxonomy: A classification system proposed by Michael J. Flynn categorizing computer architectures based on the number of instruction streams and data streams.

nodes.label: Amdahl's law
nodes.title: Amdahl's law
nodes.description: Amdahl's law: Amdahl's law: A principle formulated by Gene Amdahl describing the potential speedup of a program due to parallelization.

nodes.label: Scaling
nodes.title: Scaling
nodes.description: Scaling: Scaling: The ability of a system to handle increasing workloads by adding resources such as processors, memory, or storage.
